<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Elizabeth Jenkins: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RSC" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 June 1999</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 December 1999</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily orgName and bibCit cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DRG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 February 2001</DATE><ITEM>converted textual apostrophes and quotation marks to entity references</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>9 April 2001</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 April 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily PLACE cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily TGENRENAME cleanup, BIBCIT following P moved before P, BIBCITS TAG added</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SLB" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>20 June 2003</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>08 April 2005</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: March 2005 Specifications. Mainly tag/attribute name changes</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>5 June 2007</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>27 May 2008</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 December 2009</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>13 September 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 September 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>23 September 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 September 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 September 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>24 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>25 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>5 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>9 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>28 December 2010</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>11 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>14 January 2011</DATE><ITEM>Finished cas-ingm but I left a couple of research notes.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>14 January 2011</DATE><ITEM>cas c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>2 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>2 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft, cfb c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>29 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="LSW" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>29 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="REV" RESP="MKD" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>15 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Jenkins, Elizabeth</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P><EXTENTOFOEUVRE><GENERICRANGE>EJ, whose productive period extended from just after World War Two into the twenty-first century, was the author of half a dozen <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biographies</TGENRE></TGENRE> and twice that many <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>s (several of which portray women in the position of victims of one kind or another), besides a <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">play</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="REVIEW">book reviews</TGENRE>, and a <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">memoir</TGENRE>.</GENERICRANGE></EXTENTOFOEUVRE> Some of her works have been often reprinted.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Novels to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tortoise and the Hare</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64772" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Virginia Water, 1929"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1929-11-28" CERTAINTY="BY">By late November 1929</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Virginia Water</TITLE>, through the recent but respected publishing house of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Victor Gollancz">Gollancz</ORGNAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1452 (28 November 1929): 1000" DBREF="54246">1452 (28 November 1929): 1000</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>She worked on this book during her year of exploring <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> after graduating from university, <PATTITUDES>enthralled by the writing process more intensely than she was ever to be again.</PATTITUDES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 26" DBREF="65527">26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PDEDICATION>She dedicated this book to the elder of her two brothers, <NAME STANDARD="Jenkins, Romilly James Heald">Romilly Jenkins</NAME>.</PDEDICATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Virgina Water, prelims" DBREF="64772">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>The copy now at the <ORGNAME>University of Alberta</ORGNAME> belonged to her other brother, <NAME STANDARD="Jenkins, David Caldicott Heald">David</NAME>.</PARCHIVALLOCATION> She based the story <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">on an infatuation with a relative.</QUOTE> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PERSONAL"><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>The first publisher she approached was the firm of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Victor Gollancz">Gollancz</ORGNAME>.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <NAME>Victor Gollancz</NAME> accepted the work on the spot, <PCONTRACT><PEARNINGS>offering an advance of &pound;60 (a lot of money to a young writer at that date)</PEARNINGS> and first refusal of her next three books.</PCONTRACT> This deal cemented EJ&apos;s relationship with Gollancz as friend and mentor as well as publisher.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 30" DBREF="65527">30</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Michael, 10" DBREF="65528" QTDIN="QTDINYES">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>EJ here opens a seam she was to mine in later novels, <TCHARACTERIZATION>in tracing the <TTHEMETOPIC>emotional suffering</TTHEMETOPIC> brought to a young woman, <TCHARACTERNAME>Fanny Arne</TCHARACTERNAME>, by her <TTHEMETOPIC>brief love-affair</TTHEMETOPIC> with a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">charismatic older man, in this case a famous author</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Roger Simon</TCHARACTERNAME>. He and his alarming clutch of brothers and sisters belong to the <TTHEMETOPIC>intelligentsia</TTHEMETOPIC> (a number of whom feature in the novel in richly detailed character-sketches), as Fanny does not. Fanny has a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">small private income but works as a typist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and is an <TMOTIF>orphan</TMOTIF>, though she has a stepmother who lives in the country.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Virginia 179, passim" DBREF="64772">179, passim</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION> Roger takes her to art galleries and to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, while conscious that an end must come: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">any permanent relationship with her he never considered.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Virginia 56" DBREF="64772" QTDIN="QTDINYES">56</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Meanwhile his family decide that Fanny may <SOCALLED>do</SOCALLED> for Roger&apos;s younger, somewhat <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>odd, delicate, socially awkward brother Anthony, an aspiring painter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Anthony proposes, telling Fanny: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Apart from the fact that I&apos;m in love with you . . . . I feel that you&apos;re absolutely sympathetic to me, and to have that, it&apos;s such a marvellous, incredible sort of repose, relief&mdash;it&apos;s like bathing in the most divinely clear water, with no crabs or weeds or anything anywhere.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Virginia 173" DBREF="64772" QTDIN="QTDINYES">173</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Fanny marries Anthony; she has a son; for a while she seems happy, but her love for Roger is still at her heart. At the close of the novel she seems on the verge of <TTHEMETOPIC>breakdown</TTHEMETOPIC>, roused from lethargy only by the memory of love and suffering. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I must be living to feel such pain.</QUOTE> Roger, meanwhile, is content with the aesthetic pleasures of a connoisseur.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Virginia 288" DBREF="64772" QTDIN="QTDINYES">288</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME>Miss Cartwright</NAME>, EJ&apos;s headmistress when she was eight, wrote to congratulate her but implicitly to warn her against writing for <SOCALLED>self-glorification</SOCALLED>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 17" DBREF="65527">17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Reviews in general were excellent, as indicated by snippets quoted in her next novel, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Winters</TITLE>. Different commentators variously wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Perfection of its kind. . . . It is rare to find a work of art in which the atmosphere is so effortlessly and perfectly sustained. . . . It is very thrilling to be thus arrested.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Winters prelims" DBREF="64795" QTDIN="QTDINYES">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> found this an interesting if not wholly satisfactory work for a debut, <TCHARACTERIZATION>in which the realization of some characters (particularly Roger Simon and his sister <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Simon, Athene">Athene</TCHARACTERNAME>) set a high standard to which the rest did not quite measure up.</TCHARACTERIZATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1452 (28 November 1929): 1000" DBREF="54246">1452 (28 November 1929): 1000</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME>Virginia Woolf</NAME> in her diary called it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a sweet white grape of a book.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>EJ, reading this years later, was on the whole gratified, but felt that Woolf had put her finger on her fault or weakness, an over-reliance on transcription from life.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 31" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION> On the strength of this work<NAME>Victor Gollancz</NAME> offered EJ a three-book contract.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grimes, New York Times " DBREF="65405" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Daily Telegraph obit" DBREF="64645"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="SELF">Later, however, Jenkins found herself embarrassed by her first publication, and set out to buy what copies she could find and destroy them.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Michael, 10" DBREF="65528">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64795" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, The Winters, 1931"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PDEDICATION>She published another novel, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Winters</TITLE>, in 1931 (dedicated to her younger brother, <NAME STANDARD="Jenkins, David Caldicott Heald">David C. H. Jenkins</NAME>, though again without mentioning the relationship).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Winters prelims" DBREF="64795">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>The copy now at the <ORGNAME>University of Alberta</ORGNAME> was <NAME STANDARD="Jenkins, David Caldicott Heald">David</NAME>&apos;s own copy.</PARCHIVALLOCATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This traces the young adult lives of the grandchildren of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>upper-class matriarch <TCHARACTERNAME>Lady Winter</TCHARACTERNAME>, a tireless worker in the cause of women&apos;s emancipation</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Henry and his brother Edward are <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="orphan">orphans</TMOTIF> who live with her (both of them cheerfully <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>antifeminist, or at least sardonically critical of the Women&apos;s Movement</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>), their cousin Adelaide, another orphan, who both loves and fears her grandmother, and another cousin, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>beautiful but unthinkingly arrogant</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Caroline, whose unsatisfactory father is still alive. All the characters are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>effortlessly intellectual readers</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and books are much discussed. Caroline&apos;s exploits include <TMOTIF>cross-dressing</TMOTIF> when she runs into a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fuss</QUOTE> about <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">what girls mustn&apos;t do.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Winters 188" DBREF="64795" QTDIN="QTDINYES">188</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Caroline dies of a heart condition, but not before it is revealed that her relatives feared for her something worse: a <TTHEMETOPIC>mental breakdown or premature dementia, which is clearly though obliquely blamed on sexually transmitted disease</TTHEMETOPIC> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[f]rom her mother&apos;s side.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Winters 211" DBREF="64795">211</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The book ends inconclusively with Henry, who has been furiously in love with somebody else, proposing marriage to Adelaide and being quite piqued and indignant when she does not immediately accept him, but stipulates some time to consider her decision.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Harriet</TITLE> and more</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64773" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Harriet, 1934"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1934--">1934</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RRECOGNITIONS>EJ won the <RRECOGNITIONNAME REG="Prix Femina">Femina Vie Heureuse prize</RRECOGNITIONNAME> for her <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Harriet</TITLE>,</RRECOGNITIONS> about an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">educationally sub-normal woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who is <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">exploited and abused</TMOTIF> by her husband and his family.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="FAMILIAL">She based this story on an actual case of 1877, which she heard about through her lawyer brother <NAME STANDARD="Jenkins, David Caldicott Heald">David</NAME>.</PINFLUENCESHER> <TCHARACTERIZATION>She gave most of her characters the same Christian names as their actual originals; her work was, she believed, one of the earliest examples of such fictionalising of historical fact. She softened it a little by giving a sensitivity to the perpetrators of cruelty which she did not believe they had possessed in life,</TCHARACTERIZATION> but said later that she could never again work with such horrifying material. <PEARNINGS>The book was her first commercial success.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beauman" DBREF="64646"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 34-5" DBREF="65527">34-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEARNINGS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Harriet&apos;s understanding of life is limited, but what she understands she enjoys with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">horrid uncouthness</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (18 October 1985): 1184" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">4306 (18 October 1985: 1184</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TPLOT>She has money, which leads a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">fortune-hunting clerk</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, named in the novel <TCHARACTERNAME>Lewis Oman</TCHARACTERNAME> (in life <NAME>Lewis Staunton</NAME>) to marry her.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 33" DBREF="65527">33</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> When she proves a nuisance he takes up with another woman, and passes Harriet (while living on her money) to his brother Patrick and sister-in-law Elizabeth. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">They confine her to a barred attic and a life of privation which eventually causes the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of heroine">deaths of her</TMOTIF> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of child">and her baby</TMOTIF>.</TSETTINGPLACE> Only after her death do the authorities take notice of her obviously emaciated and lice-ridden body, and her jailors find themselves locked up in their turn.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The book received some appreciative reviews, but there were others which argued that EJ was culpable in her use of real events which were so traceable. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Time and Tide</TITLE> notice (by a reviewer whom EJ believed to be writing pseudonymously) was particularly free with its condemnation.</RRESPONSES> EJ, however, had a most interesting meeting with a woman who had worked as a servant for the actual abusive family after their release from prison. She fought shy of several suggestions that she should write another book of the same kind.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 34-7" DBREF="65527">34-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RRECOGNITIONS>In winning the <RRECOGNITIONNAME REG="Prix Femina">Femina Vie Heureuse Prize</RRECOGNITIONNAME> (which the author received at the hands of <NAME>E. M. Forster</NAME>) this book beat such contenders as <NAME>Evelyn Waugh</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Handful of Dust</TITLE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Daily Telegraph obit" DBREF="64645"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> which has proved more successful at retaining its high status.</RRECOGNITIONS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">When <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Harriet</TITLE> was reprinted in 1985, <NAME STANDARD="White, Terence de Vere">Terence de Vere White</NAME> wrote: <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE"><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Time has enriched such felicities in this stark novel as the chaplain&apos;s call on Elizabeth in her cell to tell her that her husband has died in his.</QUOTE> Elizabeth, institutionalized and unfeeling, is more interested in the <TTHEMETOPIC>prison food</TTHEMETOPIC> which is now her only pleasure.</TSETTINGPLACE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 4306 (18 October 1985): 1184" DBREF="54246">4306 (18 October 1985: 1184</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>EJ&apos;s next novels were <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Doubtful Joy</TITLE>, 1935, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Phoenix Nest</TITLE>, 1936, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Robert and Helen</TITLE>, 1944, and <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Young Enthusiasts</TITLE>, 1947 (titled from <NAME>Samuel Johnson</NAME>&apos;s description of the ambitious young scholar in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Vanity of Human Wishes</TITLE>),</TINTERTEXTUALITY> which draws on her school experiences both as pupil and teacher. <TGENREISSUE>She called <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Young Enthusiasts</TITLE> a <SOCALLED><TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">reportage novel</TGENRE></SOCALLED>, one in which the account of some trade or occupation is paramount. EJ believed this sub-genre to be one of the most interesting developments in twentieth-century fiction (while also tracing it back to <NAME STANDARD="Defoe, Daniel">Defoe</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Robinson Crusoe</TITLE>).</TGENREISSUE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Michael 11" DBREF="65528">11</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 110-12" DBREF="65527">110-12</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tortoise and the Hare</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104738" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, The Tortoise and the Hare, 1954"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1954-04-16" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-April 1954</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RBESTKNOWNWORK>EJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tortoise and the Hare</TITLE>, about a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">sweet-natured, nervous, submissive middle-class wife</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> whose marriage collapses in face of <TTHEMETOPIC>rivalry</TTHEMETOPIC> from a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>determined though not conventionally attractive woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</RBESTKNOWNWORK></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2724 (16 April 1954): 245" DBREF="54246">2724 (16 April 1954): 245</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="LITERARY">EJ revised her draft at the suggestion of <NAME>Victor Gollancz</NAME>, making cuts which she felt depleted the feeling in the novel but which he felt strengthened it.</PINFLUENCESHER> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>It was not until she re-read part of the novel late in life when she came on a copy among second-hand books for sale, that she understood how much, she said, these cuts had improved it.</RSELFDESCRIPTION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 117-18" DBREF="65527">117-18</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TCHARACTERIZATION><RPENALTIES CENSORSHIP="CENSORSHIPYES">She had to modify her portrait of Blanche, the other woman, which was based on an actual model, for fear of a libel case.</RPENALTIES></TCHARACTERIZATION> <PEDITIONS>This novel was reprinted by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Virago Press">Virago</ORGNAME> in <DATE>1983</DATE> in their <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES" REG="Virago Modern Classics">Modern Classics</TITLE> series (for which EJ declined to provide a promotional photo).</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beauman" DBREF="64646"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">Her protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME>Imogen Gresham</TCHARACTERNAME> (a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">sensitive, cultivated, and self-effacing woman married</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> to the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">brilliant and forceful barrister</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gresham, Evelyn">Evelyn</TCHARACTERNAME>), is the hare, while her neighbour <TCHARACTERNAME>Blanche Silcox</TCHARACTERNAME> (<TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>fifty-ish, unmarried, badly dressed, but wealthy, energetic, self-confident, and a force in the village community</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>) is the tortoise.</TTECHNIQUES> <TPLOT>That Evelyn should be attracted to Blanche seems unthinkable to Imogen, but as Blanche makes herself useful by chauffeuring (Imogen has never learned to drive), organising, taking over small family matters, the unthinkable becomes gradually the inescapable truth.</TPLOT> Other characters are deftly sketched: Imogen&apos;s eleven-year-old son Gavin, who despises and disregards her; Gavin&apos;s friend Tim, who finds refuge with the Greshams from his own <TTHEMETOPIC>bohemian and neglectful family</TTHEMETOPIC>; Tim&apos;s mother, <TCHARACTERNAME>Corinne Leeper</TCHARACTERNAME>, and his aunt Zenobia, both of them <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>glamorous and narcissitic</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>; Imogen&apos;s <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>platonic admirer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Paul (who values her more highly than he does his <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>young and crass wife</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>); Imogen&apos;s closest <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>woman friend, Cecil, who is engaged in a highly successful career</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> yet in the end achieves <TMOTIF>happy marriage</TMOTIF> just as Imogen&apos;s <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="unhappy marriage">marriage is disintegrating</TMOTIF>.</P><P>Imogen&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>passivity and unexpressed despair, her helpless withdrawal</TTHEMETOPIC>, might easily repel the reader as they do her strong-minded husband and her son, but Jenkins has the art of compelling empathy. Imogen and Blanche represent the passive versus the active, the imaginative or aesthetic versus the practical, and perhaps the old-fashioned versus the modern. Imogen&apos;s capacity for suffering is matched by a capacity for quiet pleasure&mdash;in the natural world, the changing seasons, the historical associations around <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> streets and buildings. <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">Emblematic is her love for some Georgian silver-plated dishes whose inner surfaces are rose-pink with the copper shining through the worn-out silver. Blanche has the dishes re-silvered as soon as she can.</TTECHNIQUES></P><P>As it becomes clear that Imogen is going to lose everything she has built her life around, she develops a distaste for being pitied. With Gavin at boarding school, Paul dead, and the fact of Evelyn&apos;s <TMOTIF>adultery</TMOTIF> no longer even lightly camouflaged (though Evelyn expects her to live with and deal with it) she moves with decisiveness to undo her marriage and undertake the rebuilding of her life. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">There is a very great deal to be done,</QUOTE> she says, as she sets about action on her own account.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS>The new life is a small-scale affair, with a spartan flat and <TTHEMETOPIC>charity work</TTHEMETOPIC>, but it is warmed and humanised by the sudden appearance of Tim, who has left his own parents and chosen Imogen to live with during the latter part of his schooldays.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The novel was criticised by some for its exclusively upper-middle-class reach&mdash;a view which was energetically countered by <NAME>Rose Macaulay</NAME> on a radio programme.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 107" DBREF="65527">107</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TTONESTYLE>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> welcomed with joy a novel where <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the most delicate perception of shades of feeling is joined to irony and wit as well as to real gentleness and sympathy.</QUOTE></TTONESTYLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2724 (16 April 1954): 245" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">2724 (16 April 1954): 245</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">Even such a severe critic as <NAME STANDARD="Leavis, Q. D.">Queenie Leavis</NAME> expressed her pleasure in this book in a quite different context in 1970.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 4510 (8 September 1989): 964" DBREF="54246">4510 (8 September 1989): 964</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">In 1993 <NAME>Hilary Mantel</NAME> observed that the author <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">seems to know a good deal about how women think and how their lives are arranged; what women collude in, what they fear.</QUOTE> She called the result <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">as smooth and seductive as a bowl of cream.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grimes NYT" DBREF="65405" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>Nicola Beauman</NAME>, in her biography of <NAME>Elizabeth Taylor</NAME>, 2009, called this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the great novels of the twentieth century.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beauman, The Other Elizabeth Taylor 213" DBREF="60388" QTDIN="QTDINYES">213</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Novelist and blogger <NAME>Amanda Craig</NAME> posted a rave review the same year, after the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Orange Prize</RRECOGNITIONNAME> ceremony. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tortoise and the Hare</TITLE>, she wrote, was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the best novels I&apos;ve ever read,</QUOTE> on a par with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Leopard</TITLE> by <NAME>Giuseppe Tomasi di Lampedusa</NAME> or <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Emma</TITLE> by <NAME STANDARD="Austen, Jane">Austen</NAME>, and she was saddened to think that Jenkins <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">is almost entirely unread and has no presence on the Web.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Amanda Craig blog, 4 June 2009" DBREF="64665" QTDIN="QTDINYES">4 June 2009</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Early Biographies</HEADING><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">Her obituary in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times</TITLE> said that EJ&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">biographies of Jane Austen, Lady Caroline Lamb, Henry Fielding and Elizabeth I established her as one of Britain&apos;s foremost women of letters.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grimes NYT" DBREF="65405" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Lady Caroline Lamb</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104735" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Lady Caroline Lamb, 1932"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1932--">1932</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE></TGENRE>, that of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Lady Caroline Lamb</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> (writer and lover of <NAME STANDARD="Byron, George Gordon,,, sixth Baron">Byron</NAME>). It was the first full-length study of Lady Caroline to reach print.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 31" DBREF="65527">31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>In 2010 <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Contemporary Authors</TITLE>, inexplicably, lists this work as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lady Caroline Brown. A Biography</TITLE>.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Not surprisingly for its date, this work looks on Lady Caroline as a romantic icon of passion rather than as a satirist or novelist. Years later Jenkins looked on her subject as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">bewitching creature</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 31" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES"> 31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">extraordinary charm</QUOTE>, but also as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">selfish neurotic</QUOTE> indulging in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">hyper-thyroid behaviour</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 32" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">EJ was delighted by appreciative responses from readers, including a descendant of the family who felt her handling was more valuable than her rather thin material.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 32" DBREF="65527">32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL">EJ&apos;s next <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Portrait of an Actor</TITLE>, 1933, took as its subject the Shakespearean actor <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Edward Alleyn</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL">(in whom her interest had been aroused while she was at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Newnham College,, Cambridge University">Cambridge</ORGNAME> by the teaching of <NAME>H. S. Bennet</NAME>).</PINFLUENCESHER><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Kirkup, Independent" DBREF="65408"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 20-21" DBREF="65527">20-21</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PINFLUENCESHER></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Jane Austen</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104734" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Jane Austen, 1938"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>12 September 1938</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RLANDMARKTEXT>EJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">critical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> of another author of the past, <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Jane Austen</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, for some of whose works she also wrote <TGENRE GENRENAME="INTRODUCTION">introductions</TGENRE>.</RLANDMARKTEXT></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1910 (10 September 1938): 580" DBREF="54246">1910 (10 September 1938): 580</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>At this date, said EJ later, there was, astonishingly, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">no complete life, including chronological discussion of works, of Jane Austen.</QUOTE> Modern scholarship, however, had just begun, largely in the work of <NAME STANDARD="Chapman, Robert William">R. W. Chapman</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 93" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES"> 93</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PEDITIONS>A second edition of Jenkins&apos;s book, published in 1948, was several times re-issued.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TTONESTYLE>This biography, full and scholarly though not footnoted, is written with a kind of nostalgia for past times.</TTONESTYLE> It opens with a paragraph on the <TTHEMETOPIC>contrast between modern ugliness and the beauty of eighteenth-century design</TTHEMETOPIC>, as seen in buildings and household objects. (The next paragraph tackles the <TTHEMETOPIC>hardships and casual brutality of eighteenth-century life</TTHEMETOPIC>.) It ends with the remark that Austen&apos;s works will long outlast <TTHEMETOPIC>the ugly or vulgar expressions of certain admired modern writers</TTHEMETOPIC>. There is perhaps some idealisation in EJ&apos;s presentation both of eighteenth-century English taste and of the Austen family, but her comments on the novels are unfailingly perceptive. Though she assesses the work of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Burney, Frances"><SOCALLED>Fanny Burney</SOCALLED></NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> as seriously flawed, she traces Austen&apos;s various comments on and uses of Burney in affectionate detail. She combines <TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">analysis</TGENRE> of <TTHEMETOPIC>plot and characters</TTHEMETOPIC> with sometimes poetically expressed appreciation. <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">She writes of the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">interlacing of the characters</QUOTE> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Pride and Prejudice</TITLE> as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the steel structure upon which the work, with its amazing buoyancy, is sprung.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Jane Austen, 222" DBREF="64791" QTDIN="QTDINYES">222</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTECHNIQUES> Though she thinks that few admirers of Austen have the same affection for <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Emma</TITLE> as for <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Pride and Prejudice</TITLE>, yet she writes eloquently of the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">brilliant and serene</QUOTE> atmosphere of the later novel, <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">strong gold light, as of early midsummer,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Jane Austen, 283" DBREF="64791" QTDIN="QTDINYES">283</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and of the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">intricate and formal</QUOTE> plot, the six connected <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">circles of delusion</QUOTE> which spring directly from the characters involved.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Jane Austen, 284" DBREF="64791" QTDIN="QTDINYES">284</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The story of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Persuasion</TITLE>, she writes, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sinks into the consciousness like a stone dropped into water, and spreads about itself widening and ever-widening rings of association, of imagination, of intuition.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1912 (24 September 1938): 609" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">1912 (24 September 1938): 609</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTECHNIQUES></P><P>EJ&apos;s work stands up well by comparison, in scope, accessibility, and sympathy, with popular accounts of Austen produced more recently. Believing that her own age was not <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">favorable to the development of aesthetic genius,</QUOTE> she was moved to conclude on the astonishing thought that the work of the great writers of the past <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">belongs to a future which will reveal more fully the beauty and the wonder of human nature, by recognizing more completely the rights of human existence.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Jane Austen, 400-401" DBREF="64791" QTDIN="QTDINYES">400-401</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The earliest reviews, said EJ, were <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">not encouraging and some were both tepid and denigratory . . . because [the reviewers] felt it was a dead bore to have to read about Jane Austen at all.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 94" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">94</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Against this background, the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> review by <NAME STANDARD="Chapman, Robert William">R. W. Chapman</NAME> must have come as a relief. Chapman judged by rigorous academic standards, although in considering the question of whether a new life of Austen was needed he did not raise the issue of possible new information. He remarked as defects: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">no chapter-titles, hardly any references, no family trees, and no index. The dates are given, but not very clearly.</QUOTE> He noted, too, the overwhelming reliance on the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Oxford University Press">Oxford</ORGNAME> edition of Austen&apos;s letters (edited by himself). Chapman nevertheless praised <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the essential rightness of her picture,</QUOTE> which, he said, might bore or bewilder but would never mislead. He commended, as if it were unusual, EJ for being <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">always willing to believe that this great artist knew what she was about . . . where other critics have been in a hurry to assume ignorance or failure.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 1912 (24 September 1938): 609" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">1912 (24 September 1938): 609</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P>EJ was happy that this book led to her involvement with the founding of the <ORGNAME>Jane Austen Society</ORGNAME> (in a campaign headed by a local resident, <NAME>Dorothy Darnwell</NAME>) and the purchase of Jane Austen&apos;s house in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Chawton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Hampshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 94-103" DBREF="65527">94-103</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Twenty years later, holidaying in Derbyshire, EJ discovered that local legend, enshrined in guidebooks, insisted that Jane Austen had visited the area and had based her Mr Darcy&apos;s Pemberley on the palatial <PLACE><PLACENAME>Chatsworth House</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Chatsworth"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Derbyshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. Jenkins, always interested in the way that local tradition imposes itself as fact, composed a <TGENRE GENRENAME="ANSWER">refutation</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Growth of a Legend</TITLE>, for the <ORGNAME>Jane Austen Society</ORGNAME>&apos;s annual report.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 44, 86-9" DBREF="65527">44, 86-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Henry Fielding</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64765" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Henry Fielding, 1947"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE" CHRONCOLUMN1="WRITINGCLIMATE1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE>14 November 1947</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ &apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">critical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> <TTHEMETOPIC><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Henry Fielding</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC> was an early volume in <ORGNAME>Home and Van Thal</ORGNAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">English Novelists</TITLE> series (in which the first was <NAME>Phyllis Bentley</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Bront&euml;s</TITLE>).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2384 (11 October 1947): 518; 2362 (10 May 1947): 227" DBREF="54246">2384 (11 October 1947): 518; 2362 (10 May 1947): 227</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>EJ attributes the series to <NAME>Una Pope-Hennessy</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 129" DBREF="65527">129</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This little book (with no notes or index) opens on an echo of Jenkins&apos;s fuller work on Austen, with a tribute to the mid eighteenth century as a time of brilliant flowering in the <TTHEMETOPIC>English novel</TTHEMETOPIC>, and a lament for the presumed <TTHEMETOPIC>decay of imagination</TTHEMETOPIC> since the death of <NAME STANDARD="Dickens, Charles">Dickens</NAME>. EJ celebrates Fielding&apos;s work with intelligent enthusiasm. She calls <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Richardson, Samuel">Richardson</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> a silly man, however, who enjoyed <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the adulation of a crew of female readers</QUOTE> but who felt <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the recoil of the puny, unexperienced male from a man of Fielding&apos;s temperament, with all the touchiness of the underbred.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Fielding 33" DBREF="64765" QTDIN="QTDINYES">33</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She writes that <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Sarah Fielding</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">must have been a very charming creature because her brother thought so in spite of his prejudice against learned women.</QUOTE> She finds <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Adventures of David Simple, The">David Simple</TITLE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">spritely and sensible, yet tedious,</QUOTE> its single recommendation being Henry&apos;s preface to the second edition.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Fielding 52" DBREF="64765" QTDIN="QTDINYES">52</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> These ideas, no matter how remote from those of scholarly readers today, were in no way out of line with academic opinion during the 1950s.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> review of this and other Fielding material, which was largely an admiring essay on the novelist, found EJ&apos;s book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">closely packed and well-managed.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2399 (24 January 1948): 50" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">2399 (24 January 1948): 50</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Group Biography</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104736" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Six Criminal Women, 1949"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>8 December 1949</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">composite biography</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Six <TTHEMETOPIC>Criminal Women</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, covering alleged <TTHEMETOPIC>murderers, fraudsters, a blackmailer, and a pickpocket</TTHEMETOPIC>, ranging in period from the fourteenth to the nineteenth century.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2496 (2 December 1949): 797" DBREF="54246">2496 (2 December 1949): 797</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">She was commissioned by <ORGNAME>Sampson Low</ORGNAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a firm known to me only by name,</QUOTE> to write this book. They chose the title but allowed her to choose her subjects.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 116" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">116</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>They included <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Ivie, Theodosia,,, Lady">Theodosia, Lady Ivie</NAME> (who in 1686 was tried for property fraud involving land east of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> ripe for development)</TTHEMETOPIC>; <TTHEMETOPIC><SOCALLED><NAME STANDARD="Young, Mary">Jenny Diver</NAME></SOCALLED> (who was hanged for picking pockets</TTHEMETOPIC> in 1741);<SCHOLARNOTE><P>EJ gives her real name as <NAME STANDARD="Young, Mary">Jane Webb</NAME>, and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> as <NAME>Mary Young</NAME>. She was called Jenny Diver from a character in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Beggar&apos;s Opera</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Mary Young" DBREF="29268">under Mary Young</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE> <SOCALLED>Madame Rachel</SOCALLED> (<TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Sarah Rachel Leveson</NAME>), a cosmetics charlatan whose pamphlet <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Beautiful for Ever</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC> appeared in 1863, and <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Florence Bravo</NAME>, who was tried for <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">poisoning</TMOTIF></TTHEMETOPIC> in 1876, and whom Jenkins was to write about in more detail later.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 116-17" DBREF="65527">116-17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>This was followed in <DATE VALUE="1955-09-16" CERTAINTY="BY">later 1955</DATE> by <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ten Fascinating Women</TITLE> (whose title, again, EJ hated but whose text she very much enjoyed writing). <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">She did not think highly of <ORGNAME>Sampson Low</ORGNAME> as a publisher,</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PERSONAL">but failed to persuade <ORGNAME>Victor Gollancz</ORGNAME> to combine and re-issue a selection from <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Six Criminal Women</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ten Fascinating Women</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 118" DBREF="65527">118</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PEDITIONS>The latter had a new London edition and its first US edition in 1968. In the <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">American</GEOG></PLACE> edition EJ apologises for taking the reader&apos;s time with her sketch of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth I, Queen">Elizabeth I</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, a decade after her monograph on that queen, but notes that the sketch produced the commission for the book.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 118" DBREF="65527">118</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2794 (16 September 1955): 542; 3454 (9 May 1968): 477" DBREF="54246">2794 (16 September 1955): 542; 3454 (9 May 1968): 477</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Fascinating prelims" DBREF="65305">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The ten women here share varying degrees and varying combinations of <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="reputation, women&apos;s">sexual, political, or literary notoriety</TMOTIF>. Two of them&mdash;<TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Elizabeth Inchbald</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Blessington, Marguerite Gardiner,,, Countess of">Lady Blessington</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>&mdash;hold the status of <TTHEMETOPIC>professional authors</TTHEMETOPIC>. Two more&mdash;<SOCALLED>Becky Wells</SOCALLED> (whom <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Orlando</TITLE> calls by her self-assumed name of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Leah Sumbel</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>) and <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Harriette Wilson</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>&mdash;were celebrities whose memoirs also give them a claim to be writers. The others are <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Martha Ray</NAME> (the singer</TTHEMETOPIC> who became a posthumous celebrity after she was <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">shot dead</TMOTIF> by her admirer <NAME>James Hackman</NAME> on <DATE>4 April 1779</DATE>), <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth I, Queen">Queen Elizabeth I</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> (also, of course, no mean writer), <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Marlborough, Sarah Churchill,,, Duchess of">Sarah, Duchess of Marlborough</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> (a sketch which EJ thought <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of my better pieces of biographical writing</QUOTE>),<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 118" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">118</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> the <TTHEMETOPIC>twelfth-century <SOCALLED>Fair Rosamond</SOCALLED> (<NAME STANDARD="Clifford, Rosamund">Rosamond Clifford</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>), the <TTHEMETOPIC>seventeenth-century <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Lauderdale, Elizabeth Maitland,,, Duchess of">Duchess of Lauderdale</NAME> (formerly Countess of Dysart)</TTHEMETOPIC></TTHEMETOPIC>, and <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Mary Fitton</NAME>, a possible candidate for identification with the Dark Lady of <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>&apos;s sonnets</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P><P>Jenkins gives little space to Inchbald&apos;s plays but provides sympathetic accounts of her two novels, doing special justice to the great <TTHEMETOPIC>set scenes of emotional intensity</TTHEMETOPIC>. She is more interested in Harriette Wilson as woman than as memoirist, yet she gives a vivid account of the memoirs. She is more interested in Blessington as hostess than as writer, and in her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lifeless and absurd</QUOTE> <TTHEMETOPIC>annuals</TTHEMETOPIC><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Fascinating 166" DBREF="65305" QTDIN="QTDINYES">166</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> than in her novels. She allows that Blessington has visual sense but judges her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">incapable of any sustained effort of imagination.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Fascinating 170" DBREF="65305" QTDIN="QTDINYES">170</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> But her biographical sketches are without exception lively and readable, and her often too dogmatic judgements never fail to imply that effort of imagination has gone into them.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Years later, for publication in 1978 by the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Reader&apos;s Digest Association Inc.">Reader&apos;s Digest Association</ORGNAME>, EJ contributed a piece on the American-born <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Neill Cream</NAME>, who had settled in London and perpetrated murders of prostitutes</TTHEMETOPIC> in the area of <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Elliott&apos;s Row</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS> in south <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> during the 1890s. She found it peculiarly thrilling to trace the footsteps of her subject through these mean streets.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 165-9" DBREF="65527">165-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>She rejected as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">out of my sphere</QUOTE> a suggestion that she should write a book on the present royal family.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 169" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">169</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Queen Elizabeth I</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64767" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Elizabeth the Great, 1958"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1958-12-05" CERTAINTY="BY">By December 1958</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">life</TGENRE> of <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth I, Queen">Elizabeth I</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Elizabeth the Great</TITLE>, which gives comparatively little attention to politics, diplomacy, or economics, but pays close attention to psychological characterization.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2962 (5 December 1958): 699" DBREF="54246">2962 (5 December 1958): 699</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="British Books, 1973" DBREF="46245">1973</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL">EJ had been interested in Queen Elizabeth since, when she was twelve, her father stood her just over half the cost of <NAME>Mandell Creighton</NAME>&apos;s book about the queen.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 17-18" DBREF="65527">17-18</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PINFLUENCESHER> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">She was first commissioned for her own Elizabeth book by the US publisher <ORGNAME STANDARD="Coward,, McCann and Geoghegan">Coward-McCann</ORGNAME> (on the strength of her essay on Elizabeth in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ten Fascinating Women</TITLE>), although <ORGNAME>Victor Gollancz</ORGNAME> then thought it important that publication should be simultaneous on both sides of the Atlantic.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PDEDICATION>She dedicated the book to her <NAME STANDARD="Jenkins, James Heald">father</NAME> and was glad that he lived long enough to see it in print (in the year marking the four-hundredth anniversary of Elizabeth&apos;s accession to the throne).</PDEDICATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Fascinating prelims" DBREF="65305">prelims</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 119, 122" DBREF="65527">119, 122</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PEDITIONS>The biography was reprinted by <ORGNAME>Phoenix Press</ORGNAME> in 2000.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> review pointed out two small errors and suggested that both Elizabeth&apos;s relationship with <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Mary,, Queen of Scots">Mary Queen of Scots</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> and the nature of England&apos;s rivalry with Spain were somewhat oversimplified here, <TTONESTYLE>but it praised the book as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">both lively and tender,</QUOTE> and also as absorbing. </TTONESTYLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2962 (5 December 1958): 699" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">2962 (5 December 1958): 699</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>Another fairly representative reviewer praised EJ&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">imaginative insight and instinctive sympathy.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grimes NYT" DBREF="65405" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> One of those who lauded this book was Elizabethan scholar <NAME STANDARD="Rowse, Alfred Leslie">A. L. Rowse</NAME>.</RRESPONSES></P><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Michael, 11" DBREF="65528">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Others</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64766" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Joseph Lister, 1960"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1960-11-25" CERTAINTY="BY">By late November 1960</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ issued a <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE"><TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> for children</TGENRE> whose hero was <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Joseph Lister</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, the discoverer of sterilization in medicine.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3065 (25 November 1960): xxvi" DBREF="54246">3065 (25 November 1960): xxvi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>This was a handsome volume, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">boldly illustrated with men and microbes</QUOTE> by <NAME>Robert Hodgson</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3065 (25 November 1960): xxvi" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">3065 (25 November 1960): xxvi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> judged that here <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the <TGENRE GENRENAME="SCIENTIFICWRITING">essential science</TGENRE> comes in not only lucidly but excitingly.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3065 (25 November 1960): xxvi" DBREF="54246">3065 (25 November 1960): xxvi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64768" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Elizabeth and Leicester, 1961"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>October 1961</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ turned back to a subject closely related to earlier work in her <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biographical</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth I, Queen">Elizabeth</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Leicester, Robert Dudley,,, Earl of">Leicester</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE> (advertised for the autumn in July this year).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3099 (21 July 1961): 447" DBREF="54246">3099 (21 July 1961): 447</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>She argued here against a sexual relationship between her two main characters. Elizabeth, she maintained, had learned from the deaths of her mother and other wives of her father to associate sex with death. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Daily Telegraph obit" DBREF="64645"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Novels</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="65425" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Brightness, 1963"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1963-11-21" CERTAINTY="BY">By later November 1963</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ published another <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Brightness</TITLE>, <TCHARACTERIZATION>with a leading character modelled on an uncle she had never known, <NAME>Romilly Ingram</NAME>, who had gone to India as a missionary and died young of smallpox in 1898.</TCHARACTERIZATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3221 (21 November 1960) 953" DBREF="54246">3221 (21 November 1963): 953</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 89-90" DBREF="65527">89-90</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>This character (considerably altered in transplanting) was not the novel&apos;s only ingredient from life. Its central episode was suggested by the trial for manslaughter of an actual <ORGNAME STANDARD="Cambridge University">Cambridge</ORGNAME> undergraduate who had killed two elderly women and narrowly missed killing a fellow student while at the wheel of his car.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 147" DBREF="65527">147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>While EJ&apos;s early novels are remarkable for not passing moral judgement on their characters, her later ones lean the opposite way. This novel contrasts two <TTHEMETOPIC>families</TTHEMETOPIC>, the better and the worse, in a manner characteristic of earlier eras of fiction. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">Both families live in New Broadlands, an imaginary Home Counties town founded <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in the Edwardian era by a community of high-minded cranks. . . . [who] combined socialism and progress with peculiar dress . . . advanced views on feminism, vegetarianism, free thinking and the upliftiing of the public mind.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Brightness 5" DBREF="65425" QTDIN="QTDINYES">5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (This place could be a satirical rendering of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Letchworth</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Hertfordshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.)</TSETTINGPLACE> The opening description reflects the novel&apos;s turn towards <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satire</TGENRE>, as does the first scene between <TCHARACTERNAME>Marion Sugden</TCHARACTERNAME> and <TCHARACTERNAME>Una Lambert</TCHARACTERNAME>, in which Marion chucks away an empty cigarette packet, while Una represses her feelings of exasperation and disapproval for the sake of preserving a friendship which has lasted half a lifetime. The Sugdens, who first came to the town as wartime evacuees from London, glad of cramped and uncomfortable lodgings, now feel <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">they were, you might say, the most important people in the town.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Brightness 12" DBREF="65425" QTDIN="QTDINYES">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TCHARACTERIZATION>Each family has a student-age son: <TCHARACTERNAME>Derek Sugden</TCHARACTERNAME> (neglected by the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>nouveau-riche father</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who works late every day, and badly <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>spoiled</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> by his mother) and <TCHARACTERNAME>Richard Lambert</TCHARACTERNAME>, the exemplary widow&apos;s son, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>questioning intellectual</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> whose gifts and talents are just beginning to unfurl. He is the character based on the author&apos;s uncle, a young man devoted to his God, his parents, and his vocation.</TCHARACTERIZATION> <TPLOT>The gift of a sports car to Derek produces disaster, and it is not Derek who dies but Richard.</TPLOT> Una is left bereft, but it seems she is still responsible for making others behave well. A whole list of people calls on her for the support which they expect her, even in this extremity, to give as well as to receive: Richard&apos;s girlfriend Faith, whose outspoken rage against the Sugdens seems likely to bring a prosecution on her, Joseph Sugden, who comes round to do something very like apologising, Marion Sugden, who is drowned in self-pity but resists any suggestion of blame for her son; and finally the aged and infirm Miss Venables, who depends absolutely on visits from Una.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> reviewer thought this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a novel of our times, a competent expos&eacute; of <TTHEMETOPIC>materistic living</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE> However, it found the book&apos;s lively topicality to be marred by oversimplification: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the Sugdens are too bad, the Lamberts too good, and the denouement too neat to make a deep impression on the reader.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3221 (21 November 1963) :953" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">3221 (21 November 1963): 953</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">EJ said, however, that she had many letters from readers moved by Richard&apos;s goodness and his early death, and that <NAME>Victor Gollancz</NAME> was particularly touched by the book.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 89-90, 147" DBREF="65527">89-90, 147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Honey</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104733" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Honey, 1968"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>19 September 1968</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">EJ published another <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, which was entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Honey</TITLE> since her publisher, <ORGNAME STANDARD="Victor Gollancz">Gollancz</ORGNAME>, thought her choice of <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Honey">Venus and Adonis</TITLE> would not be understood by the general public.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3472 (12 September 1968): 979" DBREF="54246">3472 (12 September 1968): 979</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="British Books, 1973" DBREF="46245">1973</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 147-8" DBREF="65527">147-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Honey, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">glamorous, seductive, and narcissitic second wife</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="seduction">sets out to seduce</TMOTIF> the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">schoolboy</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Brian (son of her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lazy, amiable, weak</QUOTE> husband, Roly, by his former marriage), when the death of Brian&apos;s mother deposits him reluctantly in Honey&apos;s home. EJ highlights her disapproval of Honey and Roly, her sympathy with Brian, and her approval of the more conventional but loving families of his schoolfriend Budge, and his headmaster&apos;s wife (whose then boyfriend Honey stole at an earlier stage of their lives). In the words of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> reviewer, the ending <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">tid[ies] each character into place</QUOTE> and ensures that <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="virtue rewarded">justice is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">seen to be done to the deserving.</QUOTE></TMOTIF><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3474 (26 September 1968): 1069" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">3474 (26 September 1968): 1069</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">This review, while praising <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the solid, dense, everyday texture of the material,</QUOTE> manages through the use of words such as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">worthy</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">carefully</QUOTE> to suggest that EJ&apos;s very <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">virtues</QUOTE> are boring and old-fashioned, <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="DICTION">before entering a final protest against lapses into the opposite style of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">luridly romantic phrases.</QUOTE></TTECHNIQUES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3474 (26 September 1968): 1069" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">3474 (26 September 1968): 1069</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Ordinary readers seem to have liked best the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>schoolmaster</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> characters, who were, said EJ, informed by her own teaching experience.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 148" DBREF="65527">148</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Silent Joy</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64774" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, A Silent Joy, 1992"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>1992</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ&apos;s final <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Silent Joy</TITLE>, dealt with <TMOTIF>divorce</TMOTIF>, and presented the unfashionable view that <TTHEMETOPIC>easy divorce</TTHEMETOPIC> has evil consequences.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beauman" DBREF="64646"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Biographical Works</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING>Dr. Gully</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="104732" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, Dr. Gully, 1971"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>March 1972</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dr. Gully</TITLE>, a carefully researched <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY"><TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">fictionalised</TGENRE> biography</TGENRE> or biographical novel, based on the <TTHEMETOPIC>sexual <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">affair</TMOTIF></TTHEMETOPIC> of this <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Victorian physician</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> with a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">patient forty years his junior</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, an affair which apparently led to <TMOTIF>murder</TMOTIF>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="British Books, 1973" DBREF="46245">1973</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS>The book was entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Dr. Gully">Dr. Gully&apos;s Story</TITLE> in the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS> Between portraying one of the leading characters in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Six Criminal Women</TITLE> and composing the book (which she called a novel), <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>EJ had written about the same case for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Sunday Express</TITLE>.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> When, after the book&apos;s appearance, the <ORGNAME>BBC</ORGNAME> decided to do a <PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES">television programme on Gully, <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>they rejected input from EJ,</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> but she made some changes in the <TGENRE GENRENAME="FILMTVSCRIPT">script</TGENRE> anyhow</PAUTHORSHIP> since her friend <NAME>Robert Harris</NAME> was in the leading role.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 148, 155-6" DBREF="65527">148, 155-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME>James Manby Gully</NAME> had been widowed, then separated from a second wife, and held liberal views on sex. When he met <NAME STANDARD="Bravo, Florence">Florence Ricardo</NAME>, who was forty years his junior, he had long been well-known for arguing the harmful effects of most current medications, and favouring instead the <TTHEMETOPIC>water cure which he dispensed at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Great Malvern</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Worcestershire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>. Florence was married to an alcoholic when she became his patient, and according to EJ was a widow when she became his lover. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="reputation, women&apos;s">She had the example of <NAME>George Eliot</NAME> in her mind as a model for a non-marital but committed relationship, but she found that social ostracism was more than she could bear.</TMOTIF> After she remarried a man named <NAME>Charles Bravo</NAME> in 1876, he died horribly, poisoned, as was soon established, with antimony. Both a first and a second <TTHEMETOPIC>coroner&apos;s inquest</TTHEMETOPIC> brought in a verdict of murder by persons unknown. At the second inquest the story of the sexual affair between Dr Gully and Florence Bravo emerged and caused a sensation. Suspicion fastened strongly on Florence. EJ presents the early stages in her story mostly from Florence&apos;s viewpoint, but as Florence becomes more and more unstable she switches increasingly to that of Gully: the trial (or second inquest) is presented largely through his responses (pained and critical) to the newspaper reports.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3656 (24 March 1972): 326" DBREF="54246">3656 (24 March 1972): 326</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Gully" DBREF="29268">under Gully</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Tennyson and Dr Gully passim" DBREF="64794">passim</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TTONESTYLE>Her treatment conveys sympathy and respect for Gully,</TTONESTYLE> whom she presents as a man of integrity in all his relationships.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION>EJ said this was her own favourite among her books.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Daily Telegraph obit" DBREF="64645"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME>Elizabeth Bowen</NAME> said that sitting up late reading it in bed left her (in an Irish colloquialism) lying <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">stretched for dead.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins 140" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">140</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RPENALTIES>The book roused an indignant response, however, from one reader: <NAME>Phyllis Mann</NAME>, a local historian of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Great Malvern">Malvern</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Worcestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, who had herself researched and published on Gully, but without the literary skills to attract a wide readership. She felt strongly that her territory was being encroached on.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 153-4" DBREF="65527">153-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RPENALTIES></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times</TITLE> reviewer called the book a triumph, and to <NAME>Mary Renault</NAME> it was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the best evocation of this period by a modern author that I have ever read.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3661 (28 April 1972): 495" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">3661 (28 April 1972): 495</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> suggested that EJ&apos;s handling of her material was highly effective, though it also criticised the weight of period detail as excessive.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3656 (24 March 1972): 326" DBREF="54246">3656 (24 March 1972): 326</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE"><DATE>15 June 1973</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ gave a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SPEECH">lecture</TGENRE> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Lincoln</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lincolnshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> at the annual dinner of the <ORGNAME>Tennyson Society</ORGNAME>, which was published, leaflet style, as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Tennyson, Alfred">Tennyson</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Gully, James Manby">Dr. Gully</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Tennyson and Dr Gully 20" DBREF="64794">20</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>She describes how Tennyson, suffering from <TTHEMETOPIC>depression or nervous complaints</TTHEMETOPIC>, turned to Dr James Manby Gully and his celebrated <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Great Malvern">Malvern</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Worcestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> water cure. She ranks Gully&apos;s medical abilities and his record of healing very highly. She comments briefly on some of his other patients (including <NAME>Charles Darwin</NAME>), on <NAME>Florence Nightingale</NAME>&apos;s view of him, and on traces of his relationship with Tennyson in the latter&apos;s poems. She also touches on his burgeoning interest in <TTHEMETOPIC>spiritualism</TTHEMETOPIC> and on his relationships with <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Florence Bravo</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> and with <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Daniel Dunglas Home</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> (the subjects respectively of one book she had already published and one which she was to publish some years later).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Tennyson and Dr Gully" DBREF="64794"> </BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>King and Princes</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64769" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, The Mystery of King Arthur, 1975"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>29 September 1975</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PADVERTISING>EJ&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Mystery of <NAME STANDARD="Arthur, King">King Arthur</NAME></TITLE> was advertised in July as to be published on this date.</PADVERTISING></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3829 (25 July 1975): 836" DBREF="54246">3829 (25 July 1975): 836</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL">This book was inspired by the scholar <NAME STANDARD="Rowse, Alfred Leslie">A. L. Rowse</NAME>, and by a visit to him and her publisher friend <NAME>Raleigh Trevelyan</NAME> at their houses in <PLACE><REGION>Cornwall</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</PINFLUENCESHER> <TCHARACTERIZATION>It treated Arthur not as a king but as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Romano-British cavalry commander</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> defending the country and its culture against the <TTHEMETOPIC>Saxon hordes</TTHEMETOPIC> after the withdrawal of the Romans.</TCHARACTERIZATION> <PDEDICATION>EJ dedicated the book to <NAME STANDARD="Rowse, Alfred Leslie">Rowse</NAME>.</PDEDICATION> She followed it in 1978 with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Princes in the Tower</TITLE>&mdash;about <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Edward V, King">Edward V</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, who was proclaimed King of England in April 1483, aged twelve, last seen alive (with his younger brother Richard) in the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> shortly afterwards, and presumed dead, probably murdered, before the accession of his uncle <NAME STANDARD="Richard III, King">Richard</NAME> to the throne in June the same year. For this book EJ&apos;s research included careful tracking of visual sources.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 158-160, 162-164" DBREF="65527">158-160, 162-164</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OLIS" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>A Medium</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64771" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, The Shadow and the Light, 1982"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1982-12-" CERTAINTY="C">Probably late 1982</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EJ&apos;s interest in <TTECHNIQUES>spiritualism</TTECHNIQUES> led her to write and publish a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE> of the <TTHEMETOPIC>Victorian medium <NAME>Daniel Dunglas Home</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Shadow and the Light: A Defence of Daniel Douglas Home, the Medium, The">The Shadow and the Light. A Defence</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beauman" DBREF="64646"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Some sources give the date as 1983. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Contemporary Authors</TITLE> (in 2010) gives Home&apos;s second name wrongly as Douglas.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The title comes from words by <NAME>Daniel Dunglas Home</NAME> himself.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 170" DBREF="65527">170</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> EJ&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="PREFATORYPIECE">foreword</TGENRE> argues that no impartial person looking at the evidence can suppose that his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>levitation, his fire-handling, his telekinesis</TTHEMETOPIC>, his appearing in <TTHEMETOPIC>supernatural light</TTHEMETOPIC></QUOTE> were effects produced by fraud.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive  4165 (28 January 1983): 81" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">4165 (28 January 1983): 81</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Daniel Dunglas Home was, said a reviewer of EJ&apos;s book, the most successful of all the Victorian mediums. Among his many supporters were <NAME STANDARD="Hall, Anna Maria">Anna Maria</NAME> and <NAME>Samuel Carter Hall</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Home" DBREF="29268">under Home</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EJ sets out to demonstrate that Home&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>psychic powers</TTHEMETOPIC> were real, which of course involves her in defending a metaphysical belief-system as well as an individual. According to a reviewer, her book tends to assume rather than to argue the genuineness of his powers, and to take at face value contemporary accounts of him which a moderate sceptic would class as propaganda. EJ discusses various attacks on Home during his lifetime, including <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Robert Browning</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>&apos;s treatment in <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Mr. Sludge, <SOCALLED>the Medium</SOCALLED></TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 4165 (28 January 1983): 81" DBREF="54246">4165 (28 January 1983): 81</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> review not only asserted that EJ had failed to make her case, but accused her of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">great insensitivity to the experience of grief.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 4165 (28 January 1983): 81" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">4165 (28 January 1983): 81</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">But an eminent radiotherapist friend, <NAME>Sir David Smithers</NAME>, responded with a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">strenuous reaction</QUOTE> detailing his own experiences of the uncanny, and suggesting that scientific explanations are still lacking for many such effects.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 170-1" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">170-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Minor Works</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>EJ contributed an <TGENRE GENRENAME="INTRODUCTION">introduction</TGENRE> to a volume, the seventh in <NAME>John Lehmann</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">The Chiltern Library</TITLE>, published in 1947 and containing two titles by <NAME>Elizabeth Gaskell</NAME>. In her introduction to <NAME STANDARD="Thackeray, William Makepeace">Thackeray</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Vanity Fair</TITLE>, edition of 1954, she wrote of the Osbornes&apos; house in Russell Square on the basis of her war work in one of the same set of houses. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 46" DBREF="65527">46</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><PANTHOLOGIZATION>EJ&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short stories</TGENRE> appeared in, for instance, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Third Ghost Book</TITLE>, 1955,</PANTHOLOGIZATION> and she contributed (with <NAME>Lettice Cooper</NAME> and <NAME>Margaret Kennedy</NAME>) to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Chaplet for <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Charlotte Yonge</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, 1966.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2801 (4 November 1955): 650; 3332 (6 January 1966): 7; 2350 (15 February 1947): 93" DBREF="54246">2801 (4 November 1955): 650; 3332 (6 January 1966): 7; 2350 (15 February 1947): 93</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>Her <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Young Enthusiasts</TITLE> brought her an invitation to <TGENRE GENRENAME="REVIEW">review</TGENRE> for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Guardian, The">Manchester Guardian</TITLE>, and she covered scholarship (such as <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Chapman, Robert William">R. W. Chapman</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Jane Austen: Facts and Problems</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC>), biography (like <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Margaret Kennedy</NAME>&apos;s life of <NAME>Jane Austen</NAME>).</TTHEMETOPIC> Her <TGENRE GENRENAME="REVIEW">reviews</TGENRE> included discussions of modern fiction (for instance, several <TTHEMETOPIC>novels by <NAME>Angela Thirkell</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, whom she hated, and <TTHEMETOPIC><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ophelia</TITLE> by <NAME>Viola Meynell</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 115-16" DBREF="65527">115-16</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2548 (1 December 1950): 760; 2579 (6 July 1951): 415" DBREF="54246">2548 (1 December 1950): 760; 2579 (6 July 1951): 415</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>For some months she shared with <NAME>Theodora Benson</NAME> the chore of <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER"><TGENRE GENRENAME="ANSWER">answering</TGENRE></TGENRE> readers&apos; letters sent in response to a newspaper women&apos;s-interest column. The fee (also divided) was five pounds (presumably per week). She also gave <TGENRE GENRENAME="SPEECH">lectures</TGENRE> (for instance at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Aberystwyth University" REG="University College of Wales,, Aberystwyth,, University of Wales">University of Aberystwyth</ORGNAME> on the <TTHEMETOPIC><SOCALLED>reportage novel</SOCALLED></TTHEMETOPIC>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 136-7, 111-12" DBREF="65527">136-7, 111-12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES"><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">EJ wrote a <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">play</TGENRE> as a vehicle for her friend <NAME>Baliol Holloway</NAME>,</PMOTIVES> in which he collaborated with her, supplying the theatrical expertise and especially his sense of stage timing.</PAUTHORSHIP> He played <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Charles II, King"><NAME STANDARD="Charles II, King">Charles II</NAME></TCHARACTERNAME> in a study of the king&apos;s relationship with the <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Monmouth and Buccleuch, James Scott,,, Duke of"><NAME STANDARD="Monmouth and Buccleuch, James Scott,,, Duke of">Duke of Monmouth</NAME></TCHARACTERNAME>. <PPERFORMANCE>The play ran for a week at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Theatre Royal,, Windsor">Theatre Royal</ORGNAME>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Windsor</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Berkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, to packed houses,</PPERFORMANCE> but failed to be taken up for the West End. EJ rewrote it for <NAME>Ivor Novello</NAME> to put on in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, since he thought he would play Monmouth, and wanted the spotlight shifted from the king to the pretender, but in the end he decided the role was too young for him. The <ORGNAME>BBC</ORGNAME>, however, adapted it for highly successful radio broadcasting, again with Holloway as Charles.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 125-6" DBREF="65527">125-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Memoirs</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="65527" PLACEHOLDER="EJ, The View from Downshire Hill, 2004"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="2004-09-" CERTAINTY="AFTER">By late 2004</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY>EJ titled her <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">memoirs</TGENRE> from her <PLACE><ADDRESS REG="Downshire Hill"><ADDRLINE></ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><SETTLEMENT REG="London">Hampstead</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> address: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The View from Downshire Hill</TITLE>. <PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>They were published at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Norwich</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Norfolk"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, lightly edited by her nephew <NAME>Sir Michael Jenkins</NAME>.</PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 5295 (24 September 2004): 15; 5305 (3 December 2004): 11; 5313 (28 January 2005): 32" DBREF="54246">5295 (24 September 2004): 15; 5305 (3 December 2004): 11; 5313 (28 January 2005): 32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Sir Michael wrote to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> on 24 September 2004 (in the course of debate as to who among living authors had published a book longest ago) to publicise this forthcoming work.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 5295 (24 September 2004): 15" DBREF="54246">5295 (24 September 2004): 15</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In his introduction he says he persuaded his aunt to undertake writing it, helped her with chronological ordering, and excised some passages which, because of reluctance to expose intimate details, she had left confusing or incomplete. EJ had said she could never keep a diary, or <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">put plain facts about myself down on paper without some form of distortion or synthetic colouring appearing.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, Michael, 9" DBREF="65528" QTDIN="QTDINYES">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>EJ writes here of her own career and of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">her memories of encounters in the <TTHEMETOPIC>literary <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> of the twentieth century</TTHEMETOPIC>,</QUOTE> with vivid and idiosyncratic pen-portraits of <TTHEMETOPIC>literary lions</TTHEMETOPIC>. She describes <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Edith Sitwell</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">enormous aquamarines on her fabulously long fingers,</QUOTE> and, then and later, talking <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with a weird elemental creaking yet graceful malice&mdash;uniquely original, and with bursts of high voltage pantomime humour.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jenkins, View 22" DBREF="65527" QTDIN="QTDINYES">22</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> When she does not remember clearly, she wins the reader&apos;s trust by admitting that this is the case, rather than inventing. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 5313 (28 January 2005): 32" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">5313 (28 January 2005): 32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> During her bruising encounter, as a young aspiring writer, with <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Virginia Woolf</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, she was asked if she was poor, and replied: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Well, not necessitous.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 5305 (3 December 2004): 11" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">5305 (3 December 2004): 11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Andrew Norman">A. N. Wilson</NAME>, listing for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> his choice of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">International Books of the Year 2004</TITLE>, named this as the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">best English memoir I have read for years. . . . As you would expect from that sharply brilliant novelist and subtle biographer, she manages to paint vivid scenes and often hilarious portraits in very few words.</QUOTE> He insisted that Jenkins provided a more vivid account than Woolf in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Room of One&apos;s Own</TITLE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">of the options facing a woman who wishes to live a life of the mind and retain her independence.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 5305 (3 December 2004): 11" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">5305 (3 December 2004): 11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The actual reviewer for the same journal, <NAME>Alethea Hayter</NAME>, was more measured, finding the book vivid, observant, sometimes tart, but occasionally <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rambling, jerky, or thin.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 5313 (28 January 2005): 32" DBREF="54246" QTDIN="QTDINYES">5313 (28 January 2005): 32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Reputation</HEADING><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME>Rosamond Lehmann</NAME> recommended EJ&apos;s writing to <NAME>Carmen Callil</NAME> for inclusion in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Virago Modern Classics</TITLE> series.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Callil" DBREF="51926"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Grimes, William. Books. Elizabeth Jenkins, Woman of Letters, Dies at 104. NY Times.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Jenkins, Elizabeth. The View from Downshire Hill. 2004.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Jenkins, Sir Michael. Introduction. 2004.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>